<TEXT>
a former police officer whose acquittal on 
brutality charges sparked riots here in 1980 and who was recently 
arrested on drug charges has been linked to a huge brushfire that 
shrouded miami officials said tuesday 
alex marrero 34 has been connected to charred documents found 
at the source of the 12000acre blaze that began april 8 in 
western dade county said joe subic an investigator for the state 
department of agriculture 
police suspect the burning of the documents may have been 
connected with marreros arrest in a sting operation although 
marrero himself could not have set the fire the records were set 
on fire with gasoline subic said 
the charred documents were from eastern security and 
investigations inc in miami which marrero owned and operated 
subic said the fire broke out only hours after marrero and drug 
enforcement administration agent jorge villar were arrested on 
cocaine distribution and bribery charges 
he couldnt have set the fire himself because he was in jail 
at the time subic said 
the investigator speculated that marrero could have passed an 
order to an associate that the records be burned 
arson charges will be brought against whoever started the fire 
the florida division of forestry will be billing alex for the 
cost of the fire he said estimating the cost at upwards of 
100000 
state and federal firefighters worked for more than three days 
to battle the blaze which with the help of shifting winds april 
11 sent a blanket of thick white smoke over downtown miami and 
much of south florida 
the flames forced the evacuation of 745 detainees held at the 
federal krome avenue detention center 
marrero and villar were arrested april 8 they are accused of 
providing protection for a cocaine shipment that actually was an 
undercover operation and face up to life in prison if convicted 
in 1980 marrero and three other officers were acquitted of 
charges they beat black insurance executive arthur mcduffie to 
death after a chase triggering bloody riots 
</TEXT>
