<TEXT>
a powerful 17member board should be 
established to govern higher education in louisiana as a means of 
better desegregating the states colleges and universities a 
courtappointed official said tuesday 
the suggestion was included in a longawaited 137page report 
by paul verkuil president of the college of william and mary who 
was appointed after black leaders educators and politicians were 
unable to reach an agreement to end a longrunning desegregation 
lawsuit 
the report brought the state a step closer to ending a legal 
battle that began when the us justice department filed a lawsuit 
in 1974 a threejudge federal panel that appointed verkuil will 
have the final say 
verkuils report marked a victory for gov buddy roemer who has 
been urging the legislature to establish a single board to replace 
the four bodies that currently oversee higher education in the 
state 
verkuil also said the state should make louisiana state 
university at baton rouge the major research undergraduate and 
postgraduate institution in the state with the toughest admission 
standards in louisiana 
twelve other fouryear institutions would be divided among a 
second and third tier of schools with less stringent admission 
standards and fewer postgraduate programs 
admission standards at all universities are virtually open to 
everyone now 
in recommending a single higher education board verkuil went 
against the wishes of black leaders who feared the board would be 
insensitive to the needs of louisianas two major predominantly 
black universities grambling state university in north louisiana 
and the southern university system based in baton rouge 
grambling is governed by the board of regents and board of 
trustees which oversees most of the predominantly white 
institutions southern has its own governing board 
an attorney for southern was light in his criticism of the 
recommendation 
for the historically black universities it could have been 
worse said william jefferson a democratic state senator from 
new orleans who is a leader of the legislative black caucus 
jefferson was pleased with verkuils suggestion that a 
percentage of the state budget be reserved for enhancement of 
grambling and southern although verkuil didnt recommend a 
percentage or a dollar amount 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

