<TEXT>
in a june 1984 white house discussion on 
whether to solicit thirdcountry support for the nicaraguan 
contras george bush foresaw potential trouble for the reagan 
administration 
the only problem that might come up the thenvice president 
said is if the united states were to promise to give these third 
parties something in return so that some people could interpret 
this as some kind of an exchange 
but as disclosures at oliver norths trial have shown bush 
wittingly or unwittingly quickly became involved in quid pro quo 
arrangements with third countries as part of an administration 
effort to help the nicaraguan rebels 
bush has refused to comment on his role in the contra support 
network saying he doesnt want to prejudice norths trial but the 
questions raised by disclosures in norths trial are unlikely to go 
away without an eventual response by the president 
in depicting north as a mere cog in a huge machine aimed at 
keeping the contras alive norths lawyers have disclosed that 
nine months after bush pinpointed the problem that could result 
from enticing countries to support the contras he met with 
honduran president robert suazo cordova bush announced expedited 
delivery of us military and economic aid to the central american 
country 
the month before bushs visit president reagan had approved a 
secret quid pro quo plan slipping more than 110 million in extra 
assistance to honduras in exchange for its continued support of the 
contras 
bush was copied in to receive a feb 19 1985 memo 
recommending the approach to honduras that provides incentives 
for them to persist in aiding the freedom fighters 
a feb 20 1985 memo contained the notation we want vp to 
also discuss this matter next to a discussion of the quid pro quo 
arrangement 
bush was copied in on another memo dated may 1 1985 in which 
reagan approved a 45 million increase in cia support for honduras 
after bush at the june 25 1984 meeting spelled out the 
potential trouble reagan minutes later closed the discussion with 
an admonition for secrecy 
if such a story gets out well all be hanging by our thumbs 
in front of the white house until we find out who did it reagan 
said according to a record of the meeting released at norths 
trial 
reagans periodic cautions to aides that thirdcountry contra 
assistance shouldnt be revealed were largely adhered to until 
norths trial on charges of trying to cover up various aspects of 
the irancontra affair 
the congressional irancontra committees uncovered thirdcountry 
support for the contras but failed to show that the reagan 
administration enticed the countries into providing it 
the rewards for honduras were part of the approach the reagan 
administration made to at least 11 countries seeking help for the 
contras the north trial has shown 
the honduran deal and some other quid pro quo arrangements 
spelled out in the courtroom took place before the pell amendment 
took effect in october 1985 it barred us officials from 
agreeing expressly or impliedly that foreign aid or military 
assistance to any third country would be conditioned on assistance 
to the contras 
versions of the boland amendment in effect from october 1984 to 
october 1986 banned military aid by us intelligence agencies to 
the contras 
reagans interpretation of the boland amendment according to 
testimony at norths trial by national security robert mcfarlane 
is that it simply didnt apply to the national security council 
where north worked 
but north and others saw the honduran deal as a possible 
violation of the boland amendment as reflected in a feb 20 1985 
memo by north and nsc aide raymond burghardt 
notwithstanding our own interpretations of the boland 
amendment it is very clear from the colloquy during the 
congressional debate that the legislative intent was to deny 
any direct or indirect support for the militaryparamilitary 
operations in nicaragua said the memo 
north and burghardt objected that the state department was going 
to have the us ambassador to honduras john negroponte deliver 
word of the arrangement to the honduran president north and others 
had proposed a secret emissary who would be unlikely to be called 
before congress 
negroponte who will be called upon to testify during his 
confirmation hearings for assistant secretary will undoubtedly be 
queried on whether or not such overtures were made to the 
hondurans after the boland amendment went in effect said the 
memo 
in short the decision to proceed without an emissary places 
both amb negroponte and our hopes with the hill at increased 
jeopardy we still believe that our original concept of an emissary 
is the proper way in which to proceed 
</TEXT>
