<TEXT>
the nuclear regulatory commission will be 
watching closely when pennsylvanias peach bottom nuclear plant 
starts up for the first time since onthejob sleeping by operators 
prompted the shutdown of the two plant reactors 
the nrc voted 30 monday to lift an order that had kept the 
plant closed since march 31 1987 when the commission said 
sleeping and inattention by 33 control room workers posed a safety 
threat to the public 
the operators must never again betray the special trust and 
countenance of the public nrc chairman lando zech told utility 
representatives we will be watching you very closely 
plant officials must complete a checklist of technical items 
before beginning the ascension to full power which will take 14 
weeks and be closely scrutinized by nrc inspectors 
the process is expected to begin as early as thursday with the 
withdrawal of control rods allowing a nuclear reaction to occur 
management changes by philadelphia electric have successfully 
addressed the root causes of the earlier problems the nrc 
staff said in recommending that the commissioners permit the plant 
to restart 
many of the problems at peach bottom occurred on the overnight 
or graveyard shift on at least two occasions according to nrc 
testimony in 1987 three of the four control room employees 
responsible for running the plant were asleep at the same time 
to end catnaps by operators plant officials replaced 
comfortable highbacked chairs in the control room with lowbacked 
models the nrc noted monday that the control room was brighter 
than in 1987 that low levels of radioactivity had been reduced 
within the plant and that operators had a better appearance 
of 39 operators now at the plant 24 were there at the time of 
the shutdown and all have been retrained 
a year after the shutdown james l everett stepped down as the 
chairman and chief executive officer of philadelphia electric co 
the plant operator following criticism of the handling of peach 
bottom 
philadelphia electric spokesman bill jones said there was no 
celebration at the plant marking the end of the shutdown which 
cost the company about 250 million in plant modifications 
purchases of replacement power and its share of a 125 million 
fine 
the fine largest in nrc history was split among philadelphia 
electric and the plants other three owners the others are public 
service gas and electric of newark nj atlantic electric co of 
atlantic city nj and delmarva power and light co of 
wilmington del 
philadelphia electric learned a valuable management lesson about 
monitoring nuclear reactors but it certainly has been an 
expensive lesson joseph paquette jr the companys chairman and 
chief executive officer said after the vote 
peach bottom operates two units on the susquehanna river near 
the maryland border the nrcs action on monday means one reactor 
will be able to restart with the other remaining dormant until the 
company seeks to restart it in september 
nrc commissioner james curtis missed mondays meeting because he 
was out of the country commissioner kenneth rogers did not vote 
because he once served on the board of one of the plants owners 
the nrc said 
