<TEXT>
the sweeping economic and political changes 
adopted by polish authorities are having the side effect of 
encouraging the bush administration to talk more assertively about 
a possible end to the postwar division of europe 
while announcing some new economic initiatives aimed at 
promoting lasting reform in poland president bush also alluded 
monday to the divisions that have plagued europe since 1945 
the united states has never accepted the legitimacy of 
europes division bush said we accept no spheres of influence 
that deny the sovereign rights of nations 
bushs words made clear his view that his willingness to 
increase economic cooperation with poland and other likeminded 
east bloc countries is only part of a broader agenda his ultimate 
goal is an end to both the political divisions in europe and the 
dubious distinction of that continents central region of being the 
worlds most heavily militarized area 
it was 50 summers ago that germany invaded poland setting in 
motion a series of events that produced death devastation and 
ultimately the division of the continent where bitter cold war 
confrontations were routine for a generation after the wars end 
berlin for a time was synonymous with eastwest brinkmanship 
now the talk is of arms reductions cooperation and a shift 
toward deemphasis of ideology processes that have acquired 
considerable momentum since the advent of the gorbachev era in the 
soviet union 
almost a month to the day after moscow proposed huge cutbacks in 
armies and tactical warplanes in central europe the communist 
authorities in warsaw reached agreement with opposition leaders on 
legalizing the solidarity trade union and on holding democratic 
elections 
and bush traveled to the polishamerican city of hamtramck 
mich on monday to extoll the new paths being taken by the warsaw 
leadership 
if polands experiment succeeds other countries may follow 
bush said while we must still differentiate among the nations of 
eastern europe poland offers two lessons for all 
first there can be no progress without significant political 
and economic liberalization he said second help from the 
west will come in concert with liberalization our friends and 
european allies share this philosophy 
later a senior state department official said the changing face 
of poland augurs well for the future stability of europe as 
mistrust based on differing ideologies diminishes tensions will 
abate as well said the official asking not to be identified 
we have supported and encouraged the efforts of the nations of 
eastern and central europe to become freer more independent and 
more prosperous he said 
we have believed and believe now that movement in this 
direction will create a more stable and secure europe that is in 
everyones interest including those of the ussr 
still the official said the package of economic incentives 
announced by bush will almost certainly disappoint the poles when 
implemented the measures could lead to perhaps only a marginal 
expansion in polish exports to the united states and us private 
investment in poland as well as some debt relief 
all of the steps are linked to the actual carrying out of 
polands political and economic reforms 
and as the official noted the united states and other allied 
countries can have only a peripheral impact on ending polands 
acute economic distress 
no outsider can save poland the official said 
nonetheless the mood now early in the bush administration 
contrasts markedly with the situation almost eight years ago not 
long after ronald reagan became president 
at the time poland declared martial law and the brief 
experiment in independent trade unionism there was crushed it was 
a time when reagan responded by imposing economic sanctions against 
poland when there were fears that a soviet invasion might be 
imminent 
bush acknowledged on monday how much things have changed in the 
interim not only in poland but elsewhere in the east bloc 
the winds of change are shaping a new european destiny he 
said eastern europe is awakening to yearnings for democracy 
independence and prosperity 
