<TEXT>
district of columbia mayor marion barry was 
noticeably absent when federal drug czar william j bennett held a 
meeting with area officials on his emergency plan to fight the 
capitals drug plague 
bennett insisted monday there was nothing to stop him and barry 
from working together despite bennetts statement a week earlier 
that washingtons drug problem is so out of control that serious 
questions of local politics and governance can no longer be avoided 
or excused 
barry testified before a congressional committee while bennett 
was briefing local officials on his plan to curb drug use and 
drugrelated violence in the district 
washington became the nations murder capital last year with 372 
murders most of them drugrelated so far this year there have 
been 150 slayings compared with 99 at the same time in 1988 
five homicides were recorded monday including one in which a 
female police sergeant was slain by a fire inspector who then 
killed himself in what authorities called a love triangle police 
said it was one of the bloodiest days in the city since seven 
hanafi muslims were killed at their headquarters on jan 18 1973 
barrys effectiveness in the fight has been criticized because 
of his friendship with charles lewis indicted last week on drug 
charges and a federal investigation of his own conduct 
bennett said monday that he had not spoken directly with barry 
since the plan was announced april 10 but he said barry had been 
invited to the meeting and he urged reporters to drop the 
personality issue 
we are not in the process of developing a relationship 
bennett said we are trying to respond to the drug problem this 
issue about whether marion barry and i will stand up in public and 
put our arms around each other is not the issue and you ought to 
get off it 
barry meanwhile was asking the senate appropriations 
committees district of columbia panel to assign 500 federal police 
officers to washingtons police force to handle routine police 
duties while regular city police battle the drug dealers that 36 
million proposal was not included in bennetts plan 
barry also requested congressional help in persuading the navy 
to relinquish land the city seeks for a new prison facility 
bennett had taken the city to task for failing to build a new 
500bed pretrial detention facility although it received 50 
million from congress three years ago to do so construction has 
been held up by court battles 
barry on monday also signed emergency legislation establishing a 
curfew for most teenagers and a temporary ordinance allowing 
police to bar people from gathering on city streets 
the legislation marks the citys second curfew attempt after 
the first one was challenged in court 
bennetts hourlong private meeting monday with the local 
officials was triggered by their confusion over what bennetts plan 
meant to them 
the plan called for creation of a metropolitan area task force 
of law enforcement agents with an additional 57 federal officials 
assigned to the area as well as construction of the pretrial 
detention facility and a 700bed federal prison 
the local officials were concerned about whether the war on 
drugs would end at the district boundary line and whether they 
would get stuck with a new prison or pretrial detention facility 
housing washingtons evildoers 
baltimore mayor kurt schmoke attended the sesion saying 
afterward that there were still many more questions than answers 
today 
but the prison issue was defused somewhat over the weekend when 
bennetts staff reversed earlier statements and said bennett did 
not anticipate the need for two new prisons in maryland one 
federal prison is already being planned in cumberland in allegany 
county 
but the site for the pretrial detention facility has not yet 
been decided and bennett refused to speculate on where it might be 
built 
