<DOCNO> AP890418-0097 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
states may prosecute employers for withholding 
accrued vacation pay owed fired workers the supreme court ruled 
unanimously today in a case from massachusetts 
the court said the federal employee retirement income security 
act erisa does not preempt criminal prosecution in such cases 
erisa covers employee welfare benefit plans but accrued 
vacation pay is more akin to a workers salary the court said 
except for the fact that the vacation payment has been 
deferred such payments are as much a part of the employees 
regular basic compensation as overtime pay or the payment of salary 
while the employee is absent on vacation said justice john paul 
stevens for the court 
the ruling leaves massachusetts officials free to prosecute 
richard morash president of the yankee bank for finance and 
savings 
the yankee companies inc in may 1984 acquired the financially 
troubled home savings bank 
a year later two vice presidents christopher winslow and 
william tuttle were fired winslow said the bank owed him 14520 
for 66 unused vacation days and tuttle said he was owed 11146 for 
42 unused vacation days 
state prosecutors filed criminal charges against morash after he 
refused to pay the money except for the vacation days the vice 
presidents were owed for the few months they worked in 1985 before 
their firings 
morash was accused of violating a state law that applies 
specifically to employers accused of not paying wages to workers 
including vacation benefits 
the massachusetts supreme court ruled the law was preempted by 
erisa because the vacation pay was part of the banks employee 
benefit plan states are barred by erisa from using criminal laws 
to enforce such plans the state court said 
law enforcement officials from 12 states joined massachusetts in 
urging the us supreme court to overturn the state court ruling 
the states are connecticut florida illinois maine minnesota 
new hampshire new york north carolina oklahoma vermont 
wisconsin and wyoming 
the states said federal law and enforcement mechanisms are 
inadequate to protect workers wrongfully denied vacation pay 
stevens said today that criminal prosecution is permitted in the 
case of vacation payments owed by a single employer the situation 
would be different if a separate fund was created by a group of 
employers to guarantee vacation benefits to laborers who regularly 
shift jobs from one employer to another he said 
the case is massachusetts vs morash 8832 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

