<TEXT>
volkswagen of america inc has agreed to pay 
670000 and the united auto workers 48000 so settle claims that 
they discriminated against black employees a spokesman for the 
automaker said today 
about 800 blacks could share the money under the settlement 
which is subject to approval by us district judge gustave 
diamond who is presiding over the 6yearold case he scheduled a 
june 13 hearing on the settlement 
this is not an admission of guilt on vws part or the uaws 
part said vw spokesman tom mcdonald in troy mich 
he said the defendants settled to avoid the costs of further 
litigation and to make sure that the reputation of volkswagen 
remains as high as it was when we were making cars in westmoreland 
county volkswagen closed its lone us assembly plant last year 
citing declining sales of its golf and jetta models 
individual payments would range from 70000 to a supervisor who 
said he was harassed on the job to 200 for hourly workers who were 
fired before their 90day probations expired 
any money not claimed by individuals will be used to establish a 
