<TEXT>
a muddy field beside a hillside in rural 
vermont seems an unlikely place to debate drug testing for high 
school athletes 
but the 28 members of the woodstock union high school lacrosse 
team running their drills there at have come under more scrutiny 
than theyve ever faced before because of a drug testing program 
proposed by coach charles gibbs jr 
its the first of its kind in vermont and has prompted debate 
throughout the state 
its just one little coachs attempt in one little area to 
help kids say no gibbs said 
the program is completely voluntary and his players think fewer 
than half of the squad will sign up the program probably wont 
begin for at least another week 
i think it will work but i dont have to prove to anyone i 
dont do drugs said player eli kent whos decided not to 
participate 
everyone who volunteers gibbs included will put their names in 
a hat two names will be chosen every monday and those players will 
submit to urinalysis 
a player will be suspended for two weeks if the test comes back 
positive a subsequent offense will result in a oneyear suspension 
gibbs believes the plan will help students resist peer pressure 
to try alcohol and drugs 
but not everyone looks at it that way 
to me it smacks of 1984 even though its five years late 
said school board member robert odonnell referring to the george 
orwell novel in which government looks over peoples shoulders to 
maintain a strictly controlled society 
odonnell the only member of the school board to vote against 
the plan said he believes it encourages students to try to beat 
the system rather than helping them make decisions for the future 
we need to empower them to make the right decision not to set 
up a penal measure he said 
odonnell said athletes already are asked to sign a statement 
saying they wont use drugs or alcohol he also said the school has 
a counseling program to help teenagers deal with drug abuse 
whats more students and school officials dont feel drug 
problems in woodstock are any worse and in fact may be less 
severe than in many other towns 
from what ive seen there arent any really heavy drugs at 
all said donald caffrey a junior and member of the lacrosse 
team he does not plan to participate in the testing program 
its not the first time such a program has been suggested a 
school board plan in lafayette ind to randomly test high school 
athletes and cheerleaders for drug use was upheld by a federal 
appeals court and could be implemented this fall the american 
civil liberties union is considering appealing the case to the us 
supreme court 
gibbs defended the legality of his plan in a written proposal to 
the school board 
first it is voluntary and only voluntary second there is no 
criminal penalty which attaches to testing positive he said 
adding that he didnt think it was much different from a curfew for 
team members 
the vermont chapter of the aclu does not plan to challenge the 
program because no one has filed a complaint but executive 
director leslie williams isnt keen on the idea 
it seems to me that the intentions are good here she said 
but theyre not thinking through they say that its a voluntary 
program but we all know what its like in high school its going 
to be pretty hard to say no to the program 
williams said the tests amounted to a bodily search without 
probable cause 
gibbs believes the proposal has prompted the community to assess 
its social situation and examine the example it is setting for its 
youth but he stressed that the plan is an experiment 
i think its worth it for this season to try it to see if it 
does any good gibbs said but if i find its dividing my 
team between those who sign up and those who dont its gone 
