<TEXT>
the latest education slogan from the bush 
administration is deregulation 
broached last week before a cheering audience in a union nj 
high school president bushs offer to reduce the red tape long 
associated with federal education programs was hailed as a step 
that would give school officials flexibility to better serve needy 
youngsters 
but at least a few worried that unless very carefully crafted 
deregulation might mean a return to the bad old days before the 
civil rights era when schools had no one looking over their 
shoulders to ensure that the poor the handicapped and other 
disadvantaged students got the education they were entitled to 
we want to waive some regulations for poorer communities 
allowing them to pool state and federal funds in exchange for 
higher accountability and performance bush said 
well give you the flexibility you show us the results he 
said 
bush didnt elaborate and us department of education 
officials said they had no further specifics to offer 
were still working on how to implement what the president 
said charles kolb deputy undersecretary of the us department 
of education said in an interview monday 
but the call for more federal flexibility was generally welcomed 
by educators who have long decried the paperwork of programs such 
as bilingual education vocational education migrant education 
education for the handicapped and chapter 1 which provides 
remedial programs for lowincome pupils 
clearing away needless regulations also squares neatly with 
current school reform efforts which stress more freedom for 
educators in exchange for better classroom results deregulation 
advocates point out that forcing educators to account for every 
federal nickel not only wastes time but may actually hurt children 
federal accounting rules make it difficult to serve certain 
children in regular classrooms youngsters getting remedial help 
under chapter 1 for example often find themselves separated from 
their peers for part of the school day because thats the only way 
to fulfill the requirement that such children are the sole 
recipients of the federal aid 
but school officials increasingly criticize such pullout 
programs because they tend to segregate stigmatize and label 
children with special needs 
these kids are not pulled out for any pedogogical purposes 
but only for accounting purposes said gordon ambach former new 
york state school superintendent who heads the washingtonbased 
council of chief state school officers 
i as a former chief and representing chiefs across the 
country would be pleased to see some deregulation efforts he 
said 
as a general proposal we like that agreed albert shanker 
president of the american federation of teachers some of the 
regulations have been too restrictive its meant having to pull 
kids out of classrooms to get special programs 
but others notably mary hatwood futrell president of the 
national education association believe the cheerleaders of 
deregulation may need to be reminded why congress put that red tape 
in education programs in the first place 
many of the biggest federal education programs were conceived 
during the 1960s civil rights era before that time some funds 
intended for poor or handicapped students disappeared into the 
general operating funds of school districts never reaching the 
students they were intended for 
i think we would have to look very carefuly at any effort to 
remove regulations futrell said a lot of people forget that 
the money used to be spent on equipment not for the students in 
those programs the regulations are there to make sure there are 
certain levels of quality 
such concerns indicate that while many educators may greet 
deregulation warmly in principle it could be tough to implement in 
practice 
the many groups representing migrants disabled and 
disadvantaged youngsters will certainly press bush and congress for 
assurances that deregulation wont mean that schools will no longer 
be held accountable for reaching the intended targets of federal 
programs 
