<TEXT>
the congressional joint economic committee 
responding to president bushs call for a new spirit of 
cooperation put aside nearly a decade of bickering between 
democrats and republicans and issued a bipartisan report tuesday on 
the state of the us economy 
rep lee hamilton dind the committee chairman hailed the 
consensus report the first the committee has been able to produce 
since 1980 as a breakthrough which would set the stage for 
congress and the administration to tackle such tough economic 
issues as the federal budget deficit 
during the reagan years the 20member committee of senators and 
house members became a battleground over reagan ecowith the panel so badly 
split that it was forced to issue two 
annual reports eanomic policies 
ch year one authored by democrats and the other 
by republicans 
however hamilton who took over as chairman of the panel this 
year pushed hard for a consensus report saying it was needed both 
for symbolism and substance to show that the two parties were 
willing to put aside the past decade of warfare in an effort to 
address the countrys economic ills 
this report provides a realistic accurate assessment of 
the strengths weaknesses and uncertains no 1 economic power but we 
are 
not without serious problems 
the report said that reducing the huge federal budget deficit 
was the most important economic priority facing congress and the 
administration but it did not provide any suggestions on how the 
gap between spending and revenues should be narrowed 
it also listed the need for improving the countrys education 
system as a top priority contending that failing to upgrade 
education could saddle americas economy with enormous longterm 
costs in an increasingly competitive global economy 
america is falling behind the rest of the world in promoting 
literacy and job skills even though it already spends more money 
per student than any other country in the world the committee said 
the panel cited statistics showing that the country has an 
overall dropout rate of 25 percent with rates for blacks hitting 
40 percent and for hispanics exceeding 50 percent partly as a 
consequence 13 percent of 17yearold americans cannot read write 
or count the report said 
other economic problems cited in the report were the countrys 
low personal savings rate the emergence of america as the worlds 
largest debtor nation the third world debt crisis and the 
financial difficulties of the nations savings and loan 
associations 
in each of those areas as with the federal budget deficit the 
committee did not offer any specific solutions but hamilton said 
he was convinced that a consensus was beginning to emerge in 
washington on ways to solve the various problems 
sens william roth rdel and steven symms ridaho praised 
hamilton for taking a more conciliatory approach this year but both 
warned against raising taxes as a way of tackling the budget 
deficit 
even with the joint report both democrats and republicans felt 
the need to issue separate accompanying reports the democrats used 
their report to go into greater detail on various problems facing 
the economy while the republicans touted the successes of the 
reagan tax cuts in stimulating the 6year economic recovery the 
longest peacetime expansion in history 
four democratic members of the panel rep augustus f hawkins 
of california and sens paul sarbanes of maryland lloyd bentsen 
of texas and jeff bingaman of new mexico filed individual 
statements voicing concern that the committee may have glossed over 
serious problems in its effort to reach a consensus 
bentsen said that the us trade deficit which improved 
dramatically in 1988 is expected to worsen again this year 
exacerbating our dependence on foreign capital and causing the 
us foreign debt to balloon beyond 600 billion 
sarbanes a past chairman of the committee said he feared that 
this years report conveys an inappropriate sense of 
complacency 
over the past decade we have created unprecedented imbalances 
in the budget in international trade in the accumulation of 
both domestic and international debt which suggest we are skating 
on very thin ice sarbanes said we do ourselves and our 
children a great disservice if we fail to recognize these problems 
and take steps to correct them 
