<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled tuesday that 
international airline passengers do not have to be warned by 
carriers even in the fine print that they can collect no more 
than 75000 apiece in air disasters 
in a case stemming from the soviet downing of a korean air lines 
jet that claimed 269 lives in 1983 the court said an airlines 
failure to alert passengers to the 75000 limit does not expose it 
to greater financial penalties 
by a 90 vote the justices said kal will not be penalized for 
its failure to use the proper size type on its tickets to alert 
passengers to the 75000 limit 
such warnings generally alert passengers that they must buy 
private insurance if they want additional financial protection 
while the court was unanimous in shielding kal from larger 
damages the justices were sharply divided in granting airlines 
even broader protection from costly lawsuits 
by a 54 vote the court said an international agreement known 
as the warsaw convention does not force airlines to give passengers 
any adequate warning on their tickets that there is a 75000 
damage limit 
justice antonin scalia writing for the court said the 
warsaw convention does not eliminate the limitation on damages for 
passenger injury or death as a sanction for failure to provide 
adequate notice of that limitation 
in a separate concurring opinion justice william j brennan 
took issue with the breadth of scalias opinion 
brennan said scalias opinion means airlines are free to give 
passengers no warning at all about how much they can collect under 
the courts decision brennan said the only time an airline could 
be forced to pay more than 75000 is when no passenger ticket at 
all is delivered 
the ruling permits airlines to omit any warning about their 
financial liability even in the fine print brennan continued 
notice that is not minimally legible at the least is no 
notice at all he said 
joining in his concurring opinion were justices thurgood 
marshall harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
tuesdays case has its origins with the flight of kal flight 7 
which was en route from new york city to seoul korea when it was 
shot down by a soviet military airplane sept 1 1983 the kal jet 
flew more than 300 miles off course and entered soviet airspace 
over the sea of japan 
all aboard were killed including rep lawrence mcdonald dga 
many of the victims families including mcdonalds widow sued 
kal in various federal courts the wrongfuldeath lawsuits were 
consolidated and presented to a federal trial judge here 
lawyers for the victims families in 1984 asked us district 
judge aubrey e robinson jr to declare that kal was not eligible 
for the 75000perdeath cap imposed by the warsaw convention 
a separate private pact among airlines the montreal agreement 
says the notice of the 75000 limit must be specified in print 
size no smaller than 10point type 
the kal tickets announced the limit in 8point type 
robinson ruled in favor of korean air lines and the us circuit 
court of appeals here upheld his decision in 1987 dismissing the 
suit by the passengers families 
