prime minister margaret thatcher opened a 
35nation conference on press freedom and the flow of information 
between east and west tuesday by declaring that europe will stay 
divided until all its peoples can mingle and talk freely 
in her address mrs thatcher defended her controversial ban 
last year on british radio and television interviews with members 
of the irish republican army as an antiterrorist measure 
but she said britain could not ban the satanic verses a 
novel that many moslems regard as blasphemous because the british 
author salman rushdie broke none of our laws 
foreign minister francisco fernandezordonez of spain spoke on 
behalf of the european community 
he said that despite 14 years of negotiations between western 
and communist countries anachronistic but real obstacles still 
impede the flow of information and working conditions for 
journalists are still not what they ought to be 
the monthlong conference called the information forum is an 
offshoot of the eastwest conference on security and cooperation in 
europe that conference ended this year in vienna with the 35 
participating nations promising to improve the flow of information 
including pledging greater freedom for their national media and for 
foreign correspondents 
the vienna conference was the second stage of negotiations that 
began in helskini in the 1970s 
nations taking part include every european country except 
albania the united states and canada 
east germany the only communist country to speak at the 
conference tuesday accused unspecified western journalists and 
news organizations of spreading disinformation 
only information the truth of which is established rather 
than speculation is spread in east germany said the 
delegation chief ambassador hans voss 
news agency reports of doubtful content or dubious origins 
have no place in the media of the german democratic republic 
as mrs thatcher opened the conference her officials announced 
she will visit the soviet union next year soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev visited britain this month 
he gorbachev told us of the progress of perestroika 
restructuring in the soviet union said mrs thatcher we 
welcome and support his reforms as well as the remarkable 
political change taking place in poland and hungary 
there is still a way to go she said adding there will only 
be a common european home if the occupants can mingle and talk 
freely 
she said the vienna talks had estalished the principle that 
any country is entitled to enquire about check and question the 
policies of others in the field of human rights and freedoms 
the commitments are not on a pick and choose basis trust 
is impossible when the promises we make to each other as well as to 
our own peoples are broken 
