<TEXT>
italian scientists announced tuesday they achieved 
nuclear fusion at room temperature with a different process than 
other recent cold fusion experiments have used 
they cautioned it was too soon to tell if their process would 
prove practical for generating energy 
the scientists said recent experients at the national agency for 
alternative energy in frascati just outside of rome produced 
large emissions of neutrons but too little energy to register 
emissions of neutrons particles of an atom are evidence of 
fusion 
fusion the process that powers the sun produces energy when 
the cores of two hydrogen atoms fuse in contrast conventional 
nuclear power plants use fission which is the splitting of atoms 
scientists have long searched for a way to harness nuclear 
fusion standard experiments have used extremely high temperatures 
last month an american and a british researcher said they 
produced fusion at room temperature 
but unlike that work the new italian experiments did not use 
electrical current to trigger the reaction and they did not use 
heavy water which contains a heavy version of hydrogen called 
deuterium 
the experiment is totally different from former ones said 
umberto colombo head of the national agency for alternative 
energy we have paved the way for a new road to fusion research 
what we dont know yet is if the energy generated is sufficient to 
justify practical application 
if this experiment were not of such great importance to the 
public we would never have announced the discovery at this 
point said professor francesco scaramuzzi 60 who performed the 
experiments we are still in a very preliminary phase 
scaramuzzi said that on two occasions they measured high 
emissions of neutrons after placing a sample of the element 
titanium and deuterium gas in a special metal tube and subjecting 
it to various pressures and temperatures 
the neutrons appeared in one case after applying high pressure 
and low temperature and in another at low pressure and room 
temperature 
the agency decided to begin the experiments after stanley pons 
of the university of utah and martin fleischmann of the university 
of southampton in england announced on march 23 that they achieved 
nuclear fusion at room temperature 
pons and fleischmann said their experiment using common lab 
equipment had been run for more than 100 hours and produced four 
times as much energy as it used in a similar experiment 
researcher steven jones of brigham young university in utah found 
evidence of only very low energy output 
on monday pons told a news conference in salt lake city that 
more than 60 university and private laboratories partly verified 
the claims he made last month with fleischmann 
he also said further experiments yielded even more energy and 
ran more efficiently he said a controlled fusion reaction has been 
sustained more than 800 hours in a small flask containing heavy 
water and a palladium electrode and that recent tests produced 
roughly eight times the energy consumed 
pons said researchers measured the production of 20 to 30 watts 
of electricity from the experiment or about 67 watts per cubic 
centimeter of electrode compred to 26 watts per cubic centimeter 
in the earlier experiments 
those experiments used electrolysis in which an electrical 
current was used to herd hydrogen atoms into metal electrodes 
where the atoms were apparently forced to fuse because of proximity 
scaramuzzi told a news conference after steven jones 
experiment i asked myself how important is electrolysis there 
must be more than one road to fusion 
scaramuzzi said that the energy output of his experiment at this 
scale was too low to be registered 
in a separate development the official czechoslovak news agency 
ctk said tuesday that a team of czechoslovak physicists also 
produced roomtemperature fusion through the electrolysis method 
pavol povinc who led the team of scientists from the comenius 
universitys faculty of mathematics in bratislava capital of 
slovakia announced they had achieved fusion on monday 
</TEXT>
