<TEXT>
president bush on tuesday sent congress his 
proposal to add 374000 pregnant women and children to the medicaid 
program in an effort to reduce the nations high infant mortality 
rate 
infant and maternal care is an area where we must invest in 
the future bush said in a statement i am particularly 
disturbed by the fact that the infant mortality rate for black 
infants is nearly twice that for whites 
bush announced the outlines of the initiative in february as 
part of his fiscal 1990 budget he proposed medicaid spending of 
376 billion 33 billion or 96 percent more than this years 
budget for the federalstate health assistance program for the poor 
states would pick up the cost of the added coverage 
his plan would require state medicaid programs by april 1 
1990 to cover pregnant women and mothers with infants as long as 
their incomes are within 130 percent of the federal poverty line 
this would require coverage for a single pregnant woman with an 
income of up to 10426 a household of two with an income up to 
13078 a household of three 15730 and a household of four 
18382 
states have been moving toward a threshold of 100 percent of the 
poverty line that is required by current law to be reached by july 
1 1990 and they have the option of going to 185 percent that 
option would remain under bushs plan 
currently all but 10 states cover pregnant women and infants up 
to 1 year old at 100 percent of the poverty level or more ten 
states use a cutoff of more than 100 percent according to the 
health care financing administration which administers the 
medicaid program 
the presidents plan also would require states to improve 
participation in medicaid by running outreach programs in areas 
that have high infant mortality rates and to provide medicaid 
services to pregnant women who are presumed eligible before they go 
through a formal eligibility determination 
also under the program all children under 6 who receive food 
stamps would be covered by medicaid for immunizations 
bush also proposed spending 20 million in fiscal 1990 and 1991 
on a new program to improve coordination among three federal 
programs serving women and children medicaid maternal and child 
health and the women infants and children nutritional program 
the increases in medicaid coverage would be paid for by 
reductions in the federal matching rate for state administrative 
expenses the rates currently ranging from 75 percent to 100 
percent would be reduced gradually to a uniform 50 percent 
this legislation does not do all that we want to do but it 
does do what we can do at this time bush said 
public health officials have been concerned for some time that 
infant mortality rates in the united states have not been improving 
as fast as in other nations the united states dropped from 19th in 
1980 to 22nd in 1985 among nations in the world ranked by infant 
mortality rates 
in 1985 the infant mortality rate for white americans was 93 
deaths per 1000 births while it was 182 per 1000 for black 
americans 
</TEXT>
