<TEXT>
always hardpressed for enough grain of its 
own the soviet union has been forced to import huge quantities 
from the united states and other countries partly because of 
sloppy harvesting and other wasteful practices 
the waste has long been an issue in the kremlin where 
generations of leaders have sought ways to offset the losses by 
boosting annual production goals last month soviet leader mikhail 
s gorbachev proposed a new wave of reforms 
christian j foster an agriculture department economist says 
gorbachevs proposals could bring some changes to soviet 
agriculture but their full implementation remains to be seen 
the proposed reforms were adopted by the 300member central 
committee including the reorganization of the soviet bureaucracy 
and the expansion of longterm land leasing by private individuals 
and organizations 
other reforms which are to be worked out in the coming year 
include changes in the procurement prices for seasonal farm 
products decentralizing agricultural planning and increasing 
investments in rural areas 
meanwhile according to usda estimates the soviet unions grain 
stockpile in 1988 and 1989 will decline for the first time in seven 
years 
poor harvesting storage processing and transportation 
practices cause substantial soviet grain losses foster said 
now the soviets are increasing efforts to cut these losses 
foster writing in the current issue of agricultural outlook 
magazine said that it has been virtually impossible for even 
soviet leaders to determine accurate grain supply and demand 
statistics 
one reason for inaccuracies has been the traditional soviet 
practice of reporting grain output on the basis of bunker 
weight which includes excess moisture and foreign materials or 
dockage such as weeds soil and pebbles 
foster said a soviet newspaper in may 1988 charged that the 
time has come for the leaders of the agroindustrial complex to 
restructure this strange procedure and to stop deceiving both 
themselves and us 
the kremlin last summer published for the first time information 
about the excess moisture and dockage in state grain procurements 
the government also announced that grain production figures would 
be available on a cleanweight basis this may he said 
losses to the 1988 soviet grain harvest which was reported by 
moscow at 195 million metric tons were estimated by usda at 11 
percent or 22 million tons the big 1987 harvest of 2114 million 
tons had dockage and waste losses of 14 percent or 30 million tons 
foster said the 1988 estimate reflects reduced grain output 
greater care in handling and dry harvesting conditions last 
season 
but the losses appear to be endemic in the current production 
system according to the noted soviet economist nikolai shmelev 
every year the soviet union loses as much as 25 percent of its 
grain due to poor harvesting practices bad processing and 
storage and transport difficuties 
foster said a lack of drying facilities partly accounts for the 
excessive moisture in soviet grain crops and even in dry 
weather the short growing season in the siberian regions often 
does not permit plants to dry out before harvest 
according to one authority he said a huge part of the soviet 
grain area is not harvested quickly enough resulting in yearly 
losses of 17 million to 20 million tons another authority said 
that if the harvest could be shortened by only a week or 10 days 
yields could be boosted enough to produce an additional 30 million 
to 40 million tons 
foster said the soviet unions use of grain as livestock feed 
continues to rise to record levels reflecting the governments 
desire to boost the output of meat poultry and dairy products 
but the soviets are trying to do this by increasing yields per 
animal while deemphasizing growth in animal numbers however he 
said there is reportedly much overfeeding of grains to livestock 
because of a lack of proper balance in animal rations 
for example the share of grain in mixed livestock feed produced 
by the state was reported at 684 percent in 1988 comparatively 
the grain share in us and west european mixed feeds is around 45 
percent which use much higher proportions of protein supplements 
soviet specialists report that at least 50 million to 60 
million tons of all grain used for feed in the socialized sector is 
fed nearly straight or only coarsely ground foster said they 
estimate that if properly balanced with oilmeals and other 
additives grain use could be reduced 16 million to 18 million tons 
a year 
furthermore he said improved livestock rations could free a 
significant amount of highquality wheat for human consumption 
a muchpublicized move to restrict vodka production has not had 
much effect on total grain consumption according to usdas 
estimates the soviet unions total use of grain for industrial 
purposes in 198889 will be unchanged from the five million tons 
consumed in 198788 
although production of alcohol from grain may decrease the 
use of grain in nonalcoholic beverages likely will increase 
foster said output of vodka in 1987 the latest year available 
fell another 16 percent to its lowest level in 31 years reflecting 
the gorbachev strategy aimed at curbing alcohol consumption 
</TEXT>
