<TEXT>
samuel goldwyn never read wuthering heights 
but that didnt stop him from producing the classic film with 
laurence olivier and merle oberon 
he knew little about baseball but still insisted on making 
pride of the yankees the story of lou gehrig 
he always referred to lillian hellmans play the little 
foxes as the three little foxes and he fought with warner 
bros to allow bette davis to star in the movie 
for goldwyn one of hollywoods most celebrated and colorful 
producers what mattered was a good story especially one that 
could make him cry 
he was deeply drawn to people films to emotional subjects 
said a scott berg author of goldwyn a biography 2495 
knopf an extensive biography of the film mogul his serious 
films have great emotional moments in them i think he poured all 
his bottledup emotions into those movies 
goldwyns own life had all the drama of his best films he was 
born schmuel gelbfisz in 1879 the son of a struggling warsaw 
antique dealer the young gelbfisz had no desire to remain with his 
impoverished family leaving by foot at age 16 with a vow to go to 
america and never return 
he boarded a passenger ship in liverpool late in 1898 goldwyn 
later claimed that upon reaching the united states on new years 
day 1899 he kissed the ground calling himself samuel goldfish 
the young immigrant found work in upstate new york as a glovemaker 
and eventually became a salesman earning enough money to buy a 
brownstone on manhattans upper west side 
on a muggy afternoon in 1913 his life changed forever goldfish 
left his fifth avenue office and headed uptown when he reached 
34th street he decided to check out the flickers at the herald 
square theater 
like adolph zukor louis b mayer and other immigrants goldfish 
instantly saw the potential of moving pictures and decided he 
wanted to be part of a whole new exciting world 
in 1916 he and theater producer edgar selwyn formed goldwyn 
pictures goldfish later adapted the companys name for himself 
selwyn dropped out and goldwyn went on to produce movies for more 
than 40 years 
goldwyn saw the movies as a medium by which he could invent 
this character called goldwyn berg said how could you be 
the great goldwyn making gloves i think he saw he could have a 
universal stamp 
the universal stamp what the producer would call the goldwyn 
touch was a series of powerful dramas such as wuthering 
heights dodsworth and the 1946 academy awardwinner the 
best years of our lives movies that brought tears to the eyes 
of millions of moviegoers especially goldwyn 
he brought his emotions into those movies berg said not 
just making them but watching them thats part of the key to his 
success as a filmmaker when he watched them he became an 
audience 
instead of using the sophisticated market research todays 
studio businessmen employ goldwyn just followed his heart 
if he cried it worked berg said when he saw the 
birthday sequence of stella dallas for the first time when no 
one shows up for her daughters birthday he wept and wept and 
wept then he saw the end when stellas out there in the rain and 
is pushed along by a policeman he sobbed everytime he saw the 
movie 
wuthering heights best years the little foxes and 
dodsworth were all directed by william wyler with whom goldwyn 
had a relationship best compared to that of new york yankee owner 
george steinbrenner and manager billy martin 
again and again the two stubborn immigrants fought with the 
director vowing never to work for goldwyn and the producer becoming 
enraged over wylers fondness for numerous retakes 
they both wanted the same thing as wyler told me time and 
again the author said they fought about how to make a picture 
better they were artistic fights 
goldwyns films may have made people cry but the producers 
mangling of the english language was a source of great amusement 
everyone in hollywood had a favorite goldwynism when warned 
that the little foxes was a caustic play goldwyn snapped 
back i dont give a damn how much it costs buy it he would 
back out of uncomfortable situations by insisting include me 
out 
while the filmmaker once groaned to his analyst i hate my 
mouth berg insisted that even goldwyn was amused by his 
malapropisms 
i think he reached a point where he realized just how charming 
they were his analyst would assure him that they were endearing 
people werent laughing at him they loved him for them it aint 
bad being in walter winchells column every day 
goldwyn died in 1974 outlasting nearly all his contemporaries 
as berg noted while mayer zukor and the other moguls were 
eventually kicked upstairs goldwyn remained his own boss 
i think the crucial theme is survival berg said goldwyn 
was front and center all that time he always worked against the 
tide he figured it may be tougher swimming but in the end hell 
get there 
</TEXT>
