the bush administration has temporarily blocked 
a japanese company from buying a new jersey manufacturer involved 
in nuclear weapons production according to a published report 
the new york times reported in todays editions that it was the 
first time a foreign acquisition has been stopped since enactment 
of legislation in august that empowered the president to halt 
investments that endanger national security 
the times said the tokuyama soda company of tokyo a major 
producer of chlorine and caustic soda had sought to buy general 
ceramics of haskell nj a 30 millionayear manufacturer of 
hightech ceramics for 59 million 
but the us energy department objected because of classified 
work that general ceramics is doing for the departments y12 plant 
in oak ridge tenn which makes parts for the nuclear weapons 
program the times said 
among general ceramics products are beryllium ceramics which 
are used in electronic circuits that are components of the nuclear 
weapons thought to be made at the plant the newspaper said 
the new law under which the bush administration stopped the 
acquisition established a public procedure for review and gives the 
administration the power to go to court to block such deals 
the review of the general ceramics deal was conducted by the 
committee on foreign investment in the united states which is 
composed of representatives below cabinet level of the treasury 
state commerce defense justice and energy departments and the 
office of the us trade representative 
the times reported that general ceramics is holding discussions 
with the government and with tokuyama to resolve the issues raised 
by the bush administration 
in a press release general ceramics said tokuyama soda 
expects to proceed with the proposed transaction if and when 
arrangements satisfactory to the government have been worked out 
