<TEXT>
housing construction suffering under the 
impact of rising mortgage rates fell 54 percent in march as work 
on singlefamily homes slowed to the weakest pace in more than four 
years the government said today 
the housing report by the commerce department was likely to 
intensify fears that the economy is in danger of toppling into a 
new recession housing because it is so sensitive to rising 
interest rates is often a harbinger of troubles in other sectors 
of the economy 
the report said applications for building permits a good 
indicator of future activity plunged by 137 percent in march the 
biggest monthly drop since a 14 percent decline in october 1981 in 
the early stages of the last recession 
the 54 percent decline in construction of new homes and 
apartments was the second monthly decrease following a 12 percent 
drop in february it left construction work at a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 14 million units last month as work on 
both singlefamily homes and apartment buildings weakened 
construction of singlefamily homes dropped below the 1 million 
mark to an annual rate of 994000 units the slowest pace since 
january 1985 
starts of multifamily units fell 88 percent to an annual rate 
of 403000 units 
econommists have blamed rising mortgage rates for the housing 
slowdown fixedrate mortgages are now averaging 1111 percent up 
by almost one full percentaage point from a year ago according to 
a national survey by the federal home loan mortgage corp 
the federal reserve over the past year has been pushing interest 
rates higher in an effort to dampen inflationary pressures but 
president bush and various members of congress have expressed fears 
that the fed may be in danger of overdoing the credittightening a 
growing number of economists have started to predict that a new 
recession is likely to begin by late this year or early in 1990 
the weakness in march was led by a steep 341 percent drop in 
construction activity in the northeast a region which until 
recently had been experiencing a building boom triggered by 
improving fortunes of hightechnology industries in the area 
but in march northeast construction starts fell to an annual 
rate of 149000 units the slowest building pace in the region 
since september 1983 
starts of new homes and apartments were off 52 percent in the 
south dropping to an annual rate of 546000 units while starts in 
the west dropped by 1 percent to a rate of 395000 units 
the midwest was the only region of the country to enjoy an 
increase in activity with housing construction climbing by 104 
percent to an annual rate of 307000 units 
the 137 percent decline in building permits in march followed a 
61 percent fall in february and left permits at an annual rate of 
122 million units the slowest pace since october 1982 
