president bush scored points with organized 
labor tuesday in his first postelection speech to a union audience 
but avoided any talk of his positions on the eastern airlines 
strike and minimum wage which have soured labors relations with 
the new administration 
i want this door at the white house to stay open bush told 
about 3000 delegates representing building trades unions from 
across the country i want to work with you 
the closest bush came to discussing his recent differences with 
labor was when he told the delegates theres a lot more to the 
relationship between the white house and the labor organizations 
than one issue or another we have had honest differences but 
we agree on goals and what matters is that we make progress on 
issues of shared concern 
bush was received politely by the union delegates but came under 
fire later in the day on capitol hill where democrats leading the 
laborbacked effort to raise the minimum wage chastised the 
president for refusing to negotiate with them and accused him of 
turning his back on the nations working poor 
president bush has been poorly advised to test his political 
